"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521170","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-26","<p>The following coal fired power stations currently retain Transmission Entry Capacity and are therefore capable of supplying electricity into the wholesale market when it is economic for them to do so: Aberthaw B, Cottam, Drax (units 1,4,5 &amp; 6), Fiddler’s Ferry (units 1,2 &amp; 3) Ratcliffe-on-Soar, Uskmouth, West Burton and Rugeley. The owner of Rugeley has announced its intention to close the station by the end of June 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Eggborough and Fiddler’s Ferry (unit 1) are currently part of National Grid’s Supplementary Balancing Reserve, and are capable of supplying electricity if the need arises.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-26T14:33:50.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521170/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521170/answer",,,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-24","Coal Fired Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, which coal-fired power stations are either currently producing electricity or are on standby to do so if the need arises; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","38114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521171","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-06","<p>Data on the number of smart electricity and gas meters installed in Great Britain is set out in the Government’s ‘Smart Meters, Great Britain, Quarterly report to end December 2015’, published on 31 March 2016:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-release-and-data-smart-meters-great-britain-quarter-4-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-release-and-data-smart-meters-great-britain-quarter-4-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>The roll-out is making good progress with more than 3 million meters now operating under the Programme which covers Great Britain. Northern Ireland is undertaking a separate roll-out programme.</p><p> </p><p>Data is not collected from energy suppliers in a way that allows constituency or regional-level data to be produced.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-06T14:46:46.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521171/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521171/answer",,,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-24","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many smart (a) electric and (b) gas meters have been installed in (i) Manchester, Withington constituency, (ii) Greater Manchester and (iii) the UK since the smart meter programme was implemented.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","38353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521172","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Government does not determine where new generation should connect to the network; this is a commercial decision for individual developers. The Department has, however, introduced the Capacity Market, which is designed to incentivise both new generation investment and maximise the use of existing assets to ensure that Great Britain as a whole has a secure, affordable and clean energy supply. On 6 May, Government announced that it would buy more capacity, earlier, and bring forward the start of the Capacity Market delivery period by a year to 2017/18.</p><p> </p><p>The network charging regimes (through the locational price zones at the high-voltage transmission network or connection charging regime at the lower voltage distribution network) provide price signals that encourage developers to connect where it is economically efficient to do so, helping to limit costs passed through to consumers. The charging regimes are designed by the network industry in line with the requirement to be cost-reflective, and are approved by Ofgem.</p><p> </p><p>New generation connecting above 132kv will connect to the transmission network, whereas at that level and below, it will connect to the local distribution network. In Scotland, 132kv also forms part of the transmission network.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-06T13:53:57.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521172/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521172/answer",,,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-24","Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what process her Department has for deciding whether (a) additional electricity generation is needed in a local area and (b) that generation should be centralised or decentralised","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","38403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521173","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-01","<p>The uptake and implementation of the Green Deal Home Improvement Fund (GDHIF) has been assessed as part of the wider Green Deal evaluation programme. This information can be found via the following links:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/green-deal-and-eco-evaluation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/green-deal-and-eco-evaluation</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/green-deal-assessments-research" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/green-deal-assessments-research</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/research-in-to-the-green-deal-and-eco-programme-supply-chain-follow-up-study" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/research-in-to-the-green-deal-and-eco-programme-supply-chain-follow-up-study</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/green-deal-household-tracker-survey-july-2014-dip-headline-findings" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/green-deal-household-tracker-survey-july-2014-dip-headline-findings</a>.</p><p> </p><p>By the end of February 2016, 35,330 GDHIF vouchers had been paid, following the installation of 41,263 measures. Around three quarters of the measures installed were solid wall insulation (74 per cent of measures installed). These and other latest statistics which include those relating to GDHIF are to be found via this link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/household-energy-efficiency-national-statistics-headline-release-may-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/household-energy-efficiency-national-statistics-headline-release-may-2016</a>.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-01T15:11:43.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521173/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521173/answer",,,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-24","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the performance of the Green Deal Home Improvement Fund.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","38176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521174","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-26","<p>A Notice of Inadequate System Margin is one of the tools National Grid use to maintain margins in the system and can happen at any time for a variety of reasons. Issuing a NISM does not mean that demand is about to outstrip supply: it is a notice to the market to bring forward further capacity. National Grid issue NISMs ahead of dispatching capacity from its supplementary balancing reserve, which will include 3.5GW of dispatchable generating capacity next winter. This will give any remaining capacity in the market first opportunity to respond but does not signal any significant risk of shortages. National Grid’s objective is to secure supplies and the NISM is an important tool to achieve that objective with minimum distortion to the market.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-26T14:25:17.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521174/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521174/answer",,,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-24","National Grid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what measures she is putting in place to minimise the number of Notifications of Inadequate System Margin issued by the National Grid; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","38276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521175","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-01","<p>This can be estimated by subtracting the amount of steam coal imports (mainly used by coal-fired power stations) by the total amount of coal used in electricity generation. Please see the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Imports of steam coal (thousand tonnes)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Coal used in generation (thousand tonnes)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>UK produced coal used for generation * (thousand tonnes)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion of UK produced coal used for generation %</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2013</em></p></td><td><p>42,995</p></td><td><p>50,041</p></td><td><p>7,046</p></td><td><p>14.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2014</em></p></td><td><p>35,294</p></td><td><p>38,400</p></td><td><p>3,106</p></td><td><p>8.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2015 (provisional)</em></p></td><td><p>20,631</p></td><td><p>29,342</p></td><td><p>8,711</p></td><td><p>29.6%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>* This includes stocks from earlier years.</em></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em></p><p><em>Energy Trends tables 2.1 and 2.4, available at:</em></p><p><em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solid-fuels-and-derived-gases-section-2-energy-trends" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solid-fuels-and-derived-gases-section-2-energy-trends</a>.</em></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-01T14:32:29.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521175/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521175/answer",,,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-24","Coal Fired Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what proportion of coal burnt in UK coal-fired power stations in each of the last three years was mined in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","38277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521176","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-05-26","<p>There was no cost to the public purse resulting from the Notice of Inadequate System Margin issued on 9 May.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-05-26T14:26:42.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521176/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521176/answer",,,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-24","National Grid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what the cost to the public purse was of the Notifications of Inadequate System Margin issued on 9 May 2016 by the National Grid; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","38275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521177","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-07","<p>My meeting on 12 May with Commissioner Cañete was one of a number we have had to discuss a wide range of EU Climate and Energy issues.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2016-06-07T11:59:01.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521177/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521177/answer",,,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-24","EU Emissions Trading Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether she discussed soil carbon targets when she met Miguel Arias Cañete, Climate Action and Energy Commissioner, at their meeting on 12 May 2016 on emissions targets not included in the Emissions Trading System.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","38338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521178","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-07","<p>The UK will ratify the Paris Agreement together with the EU and Member States as soon as possible. The Commission is planning to publish a proposal on EU and Member States ratification alongside legislative proposals for the Non-Traded Sector of the EU2030 Framework this summer.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2016-06-07T11:59:58.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521178/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521178/answer",,,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-05-24","Climate Change: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether the Government plans to ratify the Paris Agreement on climate change in 2016.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","38382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521179","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-06","<p>We are not aware of any waste exported for recycling which has had to be landfilled or incinerated due to contamination.</p><p> </p><p>There is a legitimate export market for quality recyclable material - but the law is clear that it is illegal to export waste from the UK for disposal.</p><p> </p><p>The regulatory framework governing waste shipments provides a mechanism for facilitating the takeback of waste to the country of export in cases where it cannot be processed as intended or in the case of an illegal shipment.</p><p> </p><p>The UK environment agencies have adopted an intelligence-led approach to identify and disrupt the movement of waste intended for illegal export. Defra has been working with the agencies to find ways of strengthening their enforcement activities.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-06-06T10:09:48.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521179/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521179/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-24","Waste: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate her Department has made of the proportion of waste exported for recycling which is contaminated and is sent to landfill or incinerated.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","38360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521180","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-06","<p>Monitoring and management of old landfill sites including in coastal areas, is a matter for local authorities under the Environmental Protection Act 1990. Part 2A of the Act provides for the local authority to carry out remediation itself where there is an unacceptable risk to human health, or the Environment Agency (EA) where there is serious pollution to controlled waters (these include coastal waters and important groundwater sources), and to then recover the costs from those who are considered liable.</p><p> </p><p>The EA is actively researching this area including supporting a research project by Queen Mary’s University to assess the impact of historic Essex coastal landfills on the local environment. The EA hopes the research findings into these historic landfill sites may provide a useful contribution to future shoreline management plans.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-06-06T10:05:40.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521180/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521180/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-24","Coastal Areas: Landfill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to (a) monitor and manage old landfill sites in coastal areas at risk of being breached by coastal erosion and changes in sea levels and (b) reduce potential future environmental consequences from such erosion.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","38359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521181","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-06","<p>The UK Government welcomes the report and recommendations from the Independent Review on Antimicrobial Resistance. A full Government response to the recommendations will be published following purdah.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-06-06T09:51:34.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521181/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521181/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-24","Livestock: Antibiotics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the recommendations of the final report of the Review on Antimicrobial Resistance, published in May 2016, if she will introduce (a) a UK-specific target for the reduction of farm antibiotic use in livestock, (b) restrictions or bans on the use in farming of highly critical antibiotics and (c) improved transparency from food producers on antibiotics used for raising meat.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","38358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521182","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-06","<p>The UK and a number of other EU Member States are calling for the European Commission to come up with proposals to ban microbeads in cosmetics at an EU level, as part of the ongoing negotiations on the proposed Council Conclusions on the EU Circular Economy Action Plan. We are also open to the possibility of the United Kingdom acting unilaterally if necessary.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this, the UK, in association with neighbouring countries in the Oslo and Paris Convention for the protection of the North East Atlantic (OSPAR), has developed the Regional Action Plan (RAP) on Marine Litter (<a href="http://www.ospar.org/documents?v=34422" target="_blank">http://www.ospar.org/documents?v=34422</a>). This RAP includes an action to evaluate all products and processes that include primary microplasti­cs e.g. microbeads and act, if appropriate, to reduce their impact on the marine environment. This programme of work will help to inform the UK’s approach to other sources of microplastics such as in washing powders, household cleaners or industrial blast media.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-06-06T16:50:27.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521182/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521182/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-24","Environment Protection: Plastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, on microbeads, of 5 May 2016, what discussions she has had with her counterparts in other EU countries on reaching common agreement on a ban on microbeads in personal care products; and if she will support a ban on microplastics in all personal care products, washing powders, household cleaners and industrial blast media.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","38357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521183","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-31","<p>Glyphosate is an important element of effective and economic weed control in crop production. It is also of value in other sectors, such as the maintenance of roads and railways.</p><p>The Government recognises the importance of effective pesticides and believes that they should be authorised where the scientific evidence shows they do not pose unacceptable risks to human health or the environment.</p><p>The European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) concluded that glyphosate met these standards and UK experts agree. The Government therefore considers that glyphosate should be approved.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-05-31T11:02:55.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521183/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521183/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-24","Glyphosate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of glyphosate usage in farming and crop production; and what her policy is on the European Commission's proposals to re-approve that use for the next 15 years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","38290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521184","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-31","<p>Defra has submitted detailed information required by the Chinese authorities, which they are reviewing. The UK Agriculture, Food and Drink Counsellor, based in Beijing, has met with the Chinese authorities to raise the importance of this agreement and we continue to press for expeditious consideration of the UK application to allow exports of UK pigs’ trotters to commence as soon as possible.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-05-31T11:08:30.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521184/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/521184/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-05-24","Pigmeat: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress her Department has made on developing the pork export accreditation protocol.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","38291"
