"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520672","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Ofcom Code on Listed Events ensures that key sporting events are made available for free-to-air channels. Our sport strategy, Sporting Future: A new strategy for an active nation, published December 2015, made clear that the Government does not propose to review this list.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T12:46:18.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520672/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520672/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Television: Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his policy is on the future availability of protected sporting events on free-to-air television; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","37986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520673","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-06","<p>Through Sport England the Government has invested a record £47.5 million in the Football Association (FA) directly since 2010 to help grow and sustain grassroots football participation in this country. That equates to £8,176,302m in 2010/11; £5,550,910m in 2011/12; £5,042,685 in 2012/13; £10,287,050m in 2013/14; £9,175,259m in 2014/15 and £9,345,964m over this last year.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2010 the Government has also provided £10m each year to improving grassroots facilities in partnership with the FA and the Premier League through the Football Foundation, and we will look to invest a further £40m over the next 5 years to the FA's Parklife programme that aims to deliver 150 football hubs in 30 English cities by 2020. Funding for Parklife began in 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is also supporting the FA's aim to increase the number of qualified coaches in this country by providing £10m over the next 5 years up to 2020, with a particular emphasis on supporting coaches from under-represented groups. This builds on the £3m The Department for Culture Media and Sport provided to the FA in 2012 for that purpose.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-06-06T12:58:09.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520673/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520673/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Football Association: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much funding his Department allocated to the Football Association in (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13, (d) 2013-14, (e) 2014-15 and (f) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","37984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520674","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-06","<p>Through Sport England's Whole Sport Plan process the FA has been challenged each year to demonstrate an increase in the number of people playing grassroots football in this country. In 2010/11 the target number of people aged 16 and over playing football for at least 30 minutes every week was 2,219,700; in 2011/12 it was 2,257,200; in 2012/13 it was 2,294,700; in 2013/14 it was 2,150,050; in 2014/15 it was 2,208,902 and in 2015/16 it is 2,267,386.</p><p> </p><p>As set out in 'Sporting Future', The Government has set out our intention to increase the number of people who engage in all types of sport and physical activity. However, from now on will move away from our historic focus on how many people are playing one sport or another at a particular moment to understanding how active people are overall. As part of this, we will also target funding at groups which have traditionally had lower participation rates, including by extending Sport England’s remit to engage people from as young as five, to help create a much healthier and more active nation.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-06-06T13:00:06.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520674/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520674/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the Government's targets for participation in grassroots football were for (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13, (d) 2013-14, (e) 2014-15 and (f) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","37985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520675","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-06","<p>The additional Government funding for the BBC World Service was agreed as part of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 and will be provided by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office. It will be used to provide additional language services subject to agreement by the Foreign Secretary and the BBC Trust.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-06T16:05:46.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520675/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520675/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","BBC World Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to pages 13 and 39 of the White Paper, A BBC for the future: a broadcaster of distinction, published in May 2016, what his Department plans to spend the £85 million of new funding for the World Service on.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","37965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520676","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Government will bring forward legislative proposals to close the iPlayer loophole by the Summer.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T12:19:34.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520676/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520676/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","BBC: Video on Demand","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he plans to bring forward legislative proposals to close the iPlayer loophole.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","37966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520677","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>The government intends to update legislation to allow clearer and more flexible payment schemes, especially for those facing difficulty in paying the licence fee. This will enable the BBC to trial alternative payment plans, including removing the requirement for individuals to pay the cost of a 12-month licence over six months. This would help those who struggle to make higher initial payments.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T12:18:41.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520677/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520677/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 17 of the White Paper, A BBC for the future: a broadcaster of distinction, published in May 2016, if he will provide details of how the more flexible payment plans for payment of television licence fees will help people on lower incomes.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","37967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520678","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Government's plans to implement a broadband Universal Service Obligation will have no impact on the Department's budget for the roll out of superfast broadband. The contracts we have put in place with Openreach mean that the more homes and businesses that sign up for superfast broadband, the more money Openreach has to return to local authorities to extend the roll out even further. So far, Openreach has confirmed more than £200 million of savings that can be reinvested, over and above the £1.7bn of public funding already allocated, and we expect more funding to be confirmed in due course. We will be reinvesting that funding to extend superfast broadband to as many additional rural homes and businesses as possible.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T12:12:39.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520678/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520678/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the savings to his Department's budget arising from the Government's decision not to automatically roll-out broadband to all households and businesses.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","37981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520679","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-06","This information is not yet available. Ofcom's call for evidence on the the design of the broadband Universal Service Obligation (USO) invites views on how a reasonable cost threshold for a broadband connection might be determined. The new broadband USO will give all households and businesses the legal right to request a fast broadband connection. This would work similarly to the telephone USO, where there is a reasonable cost threshold above which the hardest to reach properties are expected to contribute to the cost of the installation.<p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-06T15:58:47.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520679/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520679/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of how much people in rural areas will have to contribute to receive a basic 10 Mbit/s broadband connection as a result of his Department's decision not to automatically roll-out broadband to all households and businesses.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","37982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520680","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-06","<p>Ofcom has been commissioned to provide technical analysis and recommendations to help inform the design of the broadband Universal Service Obligation. One of the issues that they have been asked to advise on is how individual consumer requests for a broadband connection can be aggregated so that communities can benefit. Ofcom have published a call for inputs to support this work, which will run until 23rd June and this is available at:- <a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/consultations/broadband-USO-CFI/" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/consultations/broadband-USO-CFI/</a> Ofcom has been asked to report on its findings by the end of the year.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-06T15:59:49.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520680/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520680/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520680/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how his Department plans to allow rural communities to table collective requests for broadband connections.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","37983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520681","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>BDUK do not hold take-up data at constituency level, but do have take-up data on local projects with BDUK funding. BDUK publish these statistics for local projects on the programme’s webpage, which is publically accessible at<a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1Hs00bNsyRV1WoOt-fow3rsNXzpcKg26AsOWvk1bvJRk/edit#gid=0" target="_blank"> https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1Hs00bNsyRV1WoOt-fow3rsNXzpcKg26AsOWvk1bvJRk/edit#gid=0</a></p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T12:49:14.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520681/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520681/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520681/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the level of take-up was for superfast fixed broadband in each parliamentary constituency in the latest year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","37950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520682","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>BDUK do not hold data on the number of residential and broadband lines in each constituency.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T12:51:18.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520682/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520682/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520682/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many (a) fixed residential and (b) business broadband lines there were in each parliamentary constituency in the latest year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","37951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520683","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>The House of Commons library has produced statistics on superfast broadband coverage in each constituency based on Ofcom’s postcode data for 2015. This can be found at<a href="http://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/SN06643" target="_blank"> http://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/SN06643</a>. Thinkbroadband has independently made more recent estimates, for example at<a href="https://labs.thinkbroadband.com/local/index.php?area=eng&amp;nation=eng" target="_blank"> https://labs.thinkbroadband.com/local/index.php?area=eng&amp;nation=eng</a>.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T12:52:00.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520683/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520683/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520683/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many superfast fixed broadband lines there were in each parliamentary constituency in the latest year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","37952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520684","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>Work is ongoing on the design of the broadband Universal Service Obligation (USO) and the reasonable cost threshold. The independent telecoms regulator Ofcom will provide technical analysis and recommendations to help inform both of these, as well as identify the premises likely to be within the USO footprint. These are expected to be predominantly in rural areas, but there will also be urban and suburban homes and businesses eligible to request a connection under the USO.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","38083","2016-05-26T11:28:03.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520684/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520684/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, on what basis the contribution to broadband installation costs for the very remotest properties will be calculated; and whether there will be an upper limit on the contribution which individual households are required to make.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","38042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520685","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-03","<p>The Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport will not be publishing minutes of the events held with the creative sector as part of the BBC Charter review process. A list of the attendees of these meetings are however available in Annex 2 of the White Paper.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-03T08:31:12.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520685/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520685/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","BBC: Royal Charters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 31 of the White Paper, A BBC for the future: a broadcaster of distinction, published in May 2016, if he will publish the minutes of the roundtable events held with the creative sector as part of the BBC Charter review process.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","38084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520686","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>Work is ongoing on the design of the broadband Universal Service Obligation (USO) and the reasonable cost threshold. The independent telecoms regulator Ofcom will provide technical analysis and recommendations to help inform both of these, as well as identify the premises likely to be within the USO footprint. These are expected to be predominantly in rural areas, but there will also be urban and suburban homes and businesses eligible to request a connection under the USO.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","38042","2016-05-26T11:28:03.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520686/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520686/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 14 of the Queen's Speech 2016: background briefing notes, if he will define the terms (a) very remotest properties and (b) contributing to the cost of broadband installation in rural areas; and if he will estimate the number of properties in Westmorland and Lonsdale constituency in that category.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","38083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520687","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>Ofcom decides resource allocation and staffing levels based on the activities identified in its annual planning process. For 2014/15 the average resource cost was £63.8m and average number of staff was 787. The 2015/16 figures will be published and laid before Parliament in July.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T12:17:25.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520687/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520687/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Ofcom: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of staffing levels for Ofcom in each year up to 2028.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","38086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520688","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-06","<p>The Government has agreed that the BBC will be able to ask for voluntary payment of the licence fee from those aged 75 and over who are entitled to a free licence. We are working with the BBC to implement the legal aspects of this agreement, but the number of households which may choose to make such a payment is unknown.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-06T16:01:42.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520688/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520688/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of the number of households in which the occupants qualify for free television licences that will make voluntary payments in each year up to 2022.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","38087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520689","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>The government is in the process of drafting the Royal Charter and we expect to publish a draft version in the coming months.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T12:13:26.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520689/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520689/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","BBC: Royal Charters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when his Department plans to publish the draft BBC Charter.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","38088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520690","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-06","<p>As a result of the proposals set out in the White Paper the BBC, for the first time, will be responsible for appointing at least half of its own board members. This approach will enhance the independence of the BBC and its Board. For the public appointments to the new Unitary Board, these will be made in line with OCPA processes, with final approval coming from the Queen's Council. Appointments made by the BBC to the new board will also follow public appointments best practice, including independent members on the selection panels.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-06T16:06:45.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520690/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520690/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","BBC: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 50 of the White Paper, A BBC for the future: a broadcaster of distinction, published in May 2016, if he will publish details of the appointment process for members of the new BBC unitary board.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","38089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520691","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-06","<p>As a result of the proposals set out in the White Paper the BBC, for the first time, will be responsible for appointing at least half of its own board members. This approach will enhance the independence of the BBC and its Board. For the public appointments to the new Unitary Board, these will be made in line with OCPA processes. With particular reference to the appointment of the four national representatives the Government's intention is to follow the existing protocol of involving each of the devolved administrations in the process for the relevant representative.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-06T16:07:53.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520691/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520691/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","BBC: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 50 of the White Paper, A BBC for the future: a broadcaster of distinction, published in May 2016, if he will publish details of the public appointments process for the chair, deputy chair and non-executive members from the four nations of the UK for the new BBC unitary board.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","38090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520692","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>According to Ofcom’s Connected Nations 2015 report - based on the state of the market in May 2015 - 8% of premises were unable to access broadband speeds of 10Mbp/s and 2% of premises were unable to access broadband speeds of 2Mbp/s. These figures are likely to have reduced due to continued commercial and BDUK broadband deployment across the UK - superfast broadband access has increased from 45% in 2010 to 90%, and by the end of next year, 95% of homes and businesses will have access to superfast broadband. In addition, all premises with speeds below 2Mbp/s now have access to speeds greater than this through the Government’s Basic Broadband Scheme, and the Prime Minister has announced the Government’s intention to implement a new broadband Universal Service Obligation, with a minimum speed of 10Mbps, to help ensure no-one is left behind.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T11:43:46.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520692/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520692/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of the number of  (a) households and (b) businesses unable to access broadband speeds of (i) 10 Mbit/s and (ii) two Mbit/s in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","38091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520693","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-06","<p>Ministers have raised the issue of the time taken for service requests and repairs with senior management at BT and Openreach.</p><br />Government supports the measures Ofcom announced in its Digital Communications Review to address the problem across all communication service providers, including: raising minimum standards for the time taken to install new lines and make repairs; and encouraging proactive behaviour in the maintenance of the network. Government expects Openreach’s performance to be consistently above the minimum standard.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-06T16:04:02.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520693/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520693/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Telephone Systems: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with BT on the time taken to repair faulty telephone lines.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","38100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520694","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Government and Department set Ofcom’s overall spending cap as part of the 2015 Spending Review. Where significant changes are made to Ofcom’s remit or activities, Government will review the spending cap to ensure Ofcom is adequately resourced.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-05-26T12:16:16.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520694/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520694/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-05-23","Ofcom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his Department's planned expenditure on resources is for Ofcom in each year up to 2028.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","38085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520695","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-31","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) is developing an ambitious programme of estate rationalisation which will provide a plan for a smaller, but significantly better Defence estate to meet the needs of the Armed Forces as set out in the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015. This strategic review of the Defence estate will provide a more efficient and better infrastructure laydown in support of military capability for future generations. The MOD expects to announce the final results of this review in the autumn. When the MOD no longer has a requirement for vacant properties they will be disposed of in accordance with the standard disposal procedure.</p><p>The MOD is also reducing the number of voids by leasing out vacant properties from directly renting to the general public and through other organisations. A number of properties are also vacant awaiting the return of remaining Army personnel and families from Germany over the next three years who will require accommodation.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","37895","2016-05-31T14:50:01.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520695/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520695/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-23","Ministry of Defence: Empty Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether he has plans for the disposal of his Department's vacant properties in the UK.","true","Biography information for Tom Tugendhat","Tonbridge and Malling","Tom Tugendhat","38099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520696","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-31","<p>Four contractor-owned and operated helicopters are currently stationed in the Falkland Islands. Two AW-189 helicopters deliver search and rescue services and two S-61 helicopters deliver a medium lift capability. One River Class patrol ship (HMS CLYDE), one C-130, one Voyager air-to-air refuelling aircraft, and four Typhoon aircraft are also currently stationed in the Falklands.</p><p>In accordance with the Secretary of State's announcement to the House on 24 March 2015 (Official Report, column 1302), two Chinook helicopters are due to return to the Falkland Islands. The first of these will begin operations in July 2016.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-31T14:56:31.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520696/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520696/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-23","Falkland Islands: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) helicopters, (b) Royal Navy ships and (c) Royal Air Force aircraft are stationed in the Falkland Islands.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","38101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520697","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-31","<p>As of 24 May 2016, there were 59 Royal Navy, 483 Army and 600 Royal Air Force personnel stationed in the Falkland Islands.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-31T14:55:11.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520697/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520697/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-23","Falkland Islands: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) army, (b) Royal Navy and (c) Royal Air Force personnel are stationed in the Falkland Islands.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","38102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520698","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-31","<p>Technical equipment and personnel are available in the Falkland Islands to conduct routine maintenance on helicopters, ships and aircraft. On-island records extend only to the last 18 months and in that time no helicopters or ships have been returned to the UK for repairs. Aircraft are rotated on occasion between the Falkland Islands and other MOD locations in order to best utilise the fleet and to conduct complex maintenance.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-31T14:57:00.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520698/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520698/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-23","Falkland Islands: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what facilities are available in the Falkland Islands for the repair of (a) helicopters, (b) ships and (c) aircraft; and on how many occasions military vehicles of each such type have been returned to the UK for repairs which were not capable of being undertaken on those Islands.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","38103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520699","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-26","<p>The UK is aware that Saudi Arabia has used cluster munitions in the current conflict in Yemen, as the Saudis have themselves publicly confirmed.</p><p>Based on all the information available to us we assess that no UK-supplied cluster weapons have been used, nor have UK-supplied aircraft been involved in the use of cluster weapons, in the current conflict in Yemen.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-05-26T15:22:47.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520699/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520699/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-23","Yemen: Cluster Munitions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 15 March 2016 to Question 30727, what knowledge UK military personnel based in the command and control centre for Saudi Arabian airstrikes in Yemen had on the alleged use of cluster munitions in that conflict.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","38064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520700","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-26","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 23 May to Question number 37109.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-05-26T15:19:44.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520700/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520700/answer","20160523_37109_Armed_Forces_GCSE[1].docx","20160523_37109_Armed_Forces_GCSE[1].docx","QnA extract on Armed Forces GCSEs","QnA extract on Armed Forces GCSEs","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520700/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-23","Armed Forces: GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what opportunities the Department offers to trainee soldiers under the age of 18 to re-sit GCSEs as part of their elective personal development.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","38070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520701","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-26","<p>We have provided education and training courses to Saudi Arabian military personnel under existing Government-to-Government arrangements. These courses expose Saudi military personnel to UK policy, compliance with International Humanitarian Law and the conventions relating to the Law of Armed Conflict. We take our obligations under the Convention on Cluster Munitions seriously and continue to encourage Saudi Arabia, as a non-party to the Convention, to accede to it.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-05-26T15:22:06.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520701/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520701/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-23","Saudi Arabia: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 21 January 2016 to Question 23632, whether UK military personnel providing training and education for military personnel in Saudi Arabia on the subjects of compliance with international humanitarian law and transparency address the use of cluster munitions.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","38063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520702","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-26","<p>The UK Government takes its export control responsibilities very seriously. All export licence applications are carefully assessed on a case by case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria. A licence will not be issued if to do so would be inconsistent with any provision of the Criteria.</p><p> </p><p>The suspension of licences will be considered by my Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills in circumstances where in the light of new evidence and information it would be considered that a proper risk assessment against the Consolidated Criteria would be difficult. At this time he considers that he does have sufficient information from a range of sources for a proper risk assessment to be made against the Criteria.</p><p> </p><p>The UK ratified the Convention on Cluster Munitions on 4 May 2010 and does not licence the export of these weapons.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-05-26T15:49:13.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520702/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520702/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-05-23","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will suspend the sale of arms to countries of the Saudi Arabian-led military coalition following the coalition's alleged use of cluster munitions in the Yemen conflict.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","38075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520703","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-26","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the response I gave to the Urgent Question tabled by the hon. Member for Ochil and South Perthshire (Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh) on 24 May 2016 (Official Report, column 401).</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-05-26T15:21:23.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520703/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520703/answer","20160524_UQ_on_Yemen_Cluster_Munitions[1].docx","20160524_UQ_on_Yemen_Cluster_Munitions[1].docx","Hansard extract on Yemen: Cluster Munitions","Hansard extract on Yemen: Cluster Munitions","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520703/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-05-23","Yemen: Cluster Munitions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether cluster bombs used in the Yemeni civil war are of British manufacture.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","38041"
