"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520719","Department for Education","false","2016-05-26","<p>The cost of the nine National Schools Commissioner Roadshows during June and July 2016 will be met from within Schools Commissioner’s Group (SCG) allocated programme budget. The programme budget is to cover the costs related to events and other communications activities. For the 2016/17 financial year, this budget is £425k.</p><p> </p><p>It is expected that approximately 1,500 system leaders will attend the nine National Schools Commissioner Roadshows taking place in June and July 2016.</p><p> </p><p>There was no specific allocation made for travel and subsistence costs for officials related to the National Schools Commissioner Roadshows during June and July 2016. These costs will be met from within SCG allocated administrative budget.</p><p> </p><p>An official in each of the RSC offices has been involved in organising the nine National Schools Commissioners roadshows, supported by a lead in SCG. We expect approximately five officials to attend each roadshow, plus the National Schools Commissioner and the relevant Regional School Commissioner (RSC).</p><p> </p><p>There has been no budget allocated to advertising the National Schools Commissioner Roadshows.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","37917 ; 37919 ; 37920 ; 37921","2016-05-26T15:54:10.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520719/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520719/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-23","Schools Commissioner: Exhibitions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many people she expects to attend each of the National Schools Commissioner Roadshow events during June and July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","37918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520720","Department for Education","false","2016-06-01","<p>The National Curriculum, taught from September 2014, focuses on the essential knowledge so that teachers can design a wider school curriculum that best meets the needs of their pupils.</p><p> </p><p>The programmes of study for science include the opportunity to teach children about different animals, their needs for survival and their environment. Beyond the prescribed curriculum, schools have the freedom to teach subjects or topics, such as animal welfare, to ensure that children receive a rounded education.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-06-01T14:51:28.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520720/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520720/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-23","Animal Welfare: Curriculum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if the Government will take steps to incorporate animal welfare into the national curriculum for primary school children in England.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","37861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520721","Department for Education","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Secretary of State has already announced the Government’s plans to introduce resits in Year 7. This announcement can found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/nicky-morgan-no-tolerance-of-areas-where-majority-of-pupils-fail" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/nicky-morgan-no-tolerance-of-areas-where-majority-of-pupils-fail</a>.</p><p> </p><p>We have been clear that the resits will not be implemented in the next academic year and that we will engage with the education sector to make sure the tests are introduced in a way that works for schools. Further information will be provided in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-05-26T15:57:00.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520721/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520721/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-23","National Curriculum Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she still plans to introduce compulsory resit tests in (a) English reading and (b) mathematics for year 7 pupils who do not reach the required standard at the end of key stage 2.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","37790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520722","Department for Education","false","2016-05-26","<p>All teachers recommended for the award of qualified teacher status (QTS) must demonstrate that they meet the Teachers’ Standards in full, at the appropriate level (available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teachers-standards" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teachers-standards</a>). Trainees undertaking a course of initial teacher training must also satisfy the requirements of the Secretary of State’s Criteria for ITT (available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-criteria" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-criteria</a>), including having passed the professional skills tests in literacy and numeracy.</p><p> </p><p>Our recent White Paper, <em>Educational Excellence Everywhere</em>, set out our proposals to replace the current QTS with a new, more challenging accreditation based on teachers’ effectiveness in the classroom. We will be setting out further detail of how and when we intend to implement the new system shortly.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-05-26T15:56:21.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520722/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520722/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-23","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the statutory framework is for the accreditation of teachers in England; and whether her Department has plans to change that framework.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","37791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520723","Department for Education","false","2016-06-09","<p>The Department does not have an annual food budget. Catering services are provided via a contract with Interserve Plc, and is operated on a nil subsidy basis.</p><p> </p><p>Annual spend is determined by the contractor and is informed by private sales to members of staff.</p><p> </p><p>Approximately 60% of products across all food and drink categories were sourced from British producers as of March 2016. This proportion reflects that a large volume of food and drink sold includes non-indigenous products such as rice, tea and coffee.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-06-09T16:38:25.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520723/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520723/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-23","Department for Education: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the annual budget is for food produced for her Department's offices; and what proportion of food produced for her Department was sourced from British producers in the last period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","37826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520724","Department for Education","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Government’s White Paper, <em>Educational Excellence Everywhere</em>, confirmed that we intend to use a new set of quality criteria to determine how initial teacher training (ITT) places are allocated to training providers in future, ensuring that training is concentrated with the highest-quality providers. On the basis of these criteria, which will include factors such as the quality of trainees recruited, the quality of the training programmes, and the quality of outcomes for trainees, we will designate some providers as Centres of Excellence. We expect to set out further details of the quality criteria that will apply for the 2017/18 training year, and which providers will be designated as Centres of Excellence, when we confirm the methodology for allocating places, which is currently under discussion.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education has actively been engaging the ITT sector in discussions about the proposals in the White Paper, including the establishment of ITT Centres of Excellence. Engagement to date has included a series of roundtable discussion events for university- and school-led providers and their representative bodies, such as the Universities’ Council for the Education of Teachers (UCET) and the National Association of School-Based Teacher Trainers (NASBTT).</p><p> </p><p>We expect to confirm the allocations methodology for 2017/18 after further consultation with providers and their representative organisations over the summer, in time for the start of recruitment in the autumn term.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","37930 ; 37932","2016-05-26T15:55:16.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520724/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520724/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-23","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to paragraph 2.28 of the White Paper, Educational Excellence Everywhere, published in March 2016, with which (a) individuals, (b) organisations and (c) universities she has had discussions regarding the establishment of centres for excellence in initial teacher training.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","37931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520725","Department for Education","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Government’s White Paper, <em>Educational Excellence Everywhere</em>, confirmed that we intend to use a new set of quality criteria to determine how initial teacher training (ITT) places are allocated to training providers in future, ensuring that training is concentrated with the highest-quality providers. On the basis of these criteria, which will include factors such as the quality of trainees recruited, the quality of the training programmes, and the quality of outcomes for trainees, we will designate some providers as Centres of Excellence. We expect to set out further details of the quality criteria that will apply for the 2017/18 training year, and which providers will be designated as Centres of Excellence, when we confirm the methodology for allocating places, which is currently under discussion.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education has actively been engaging the ITT sector in discussions about the proposals in the White Paper, including the establishment of ITT Centres of Excellence. Engagement to date has included a series of roundtable discussion events for university- and school-led providers and their representative bodies, such as the Universities’ Council for the Education of Teachers (UCET) and the National Association of School-Based Teacher Trainers (NASBTT).</p><p> </p><p>We expect to confirm the allocations methodology for 2017/18 after further consultation with providers and their representative organisations over the summer, in time for the start of recruitment in the autumn term.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","37930 ; 37931","2016-05-26T15:55:16.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520725/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520725/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-23","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to paragraph 2.28 of the White Paper, Educational Excellence Everywhere, published in March 2016, when her Department plans to consult sector bodies on the proposed creation of centres for excellence for initial teacher training; and how that consultation will take place.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","37932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520726","Department for Education","false","2016-05-26","<p>The Government’s White Paper, <em>Educational Excellence Everywhere</em>, confirmed that we intend to use a new set of quality criteria to determine how initial teacher training (ITT) places are allocated to training providers in future, ensuring that training is concentrated with the highest-quality providers. On the basis of these criteria, which will include factors such as the quality of trainees recruited, the quality of the training programmes, and the quality of outcomes for trainees, we will designate some providers as Centres of Excellence. We expect to set out further details of the quality criteria that will apply for the 2017/18 training year, and which providers will be designated as Centres of Excellence, when we confirm the methodology for allocating places, which is currently under discussion.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education has actively been engaging the ITT sector in discussions about the proposals in the White Paper, including the establishment of ITT Centres of Excellence. Engagement to date has included a series of roundtable discussion events for university- and school-led providers and their representative bodies, such as the Universities’ Council for the Education of Teachers (UCET) and the National Association of School-Based Teacher Trainers (NASBTT).</p><p> </p><p>We expect to confirm the allocations methodology for 2017/18 after further consultation with providers and their representative organisations over the summer, in time for the start of recruitment in the autumn term.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","37931 ; 37932","2016-05-26T15:55:16.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520726/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/520726/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-05-23","Teachers: Training","